1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:01,804
Also I'm retiring.

2
00:00:01,839 --> 00:00:03,439
That's three, Garry.

3
00:00:03,474 --> 00:00:05,541
But we're probably due
for some good news.

4
00:00:05,576 --> 00:00:06,743
Good evening.

5
00:00:06,777 --> 00:00:08,311
I come to you tonight
with some good news...

6
00:00:08,345 --> 00:00:09,679
Hey.

7
00:00:09,713 --> 00:00:12,014
Is not a sentence I will be
saying to you right now,

8
00:00:12,049 --> 00:00:15,952
because beloved Pawnee Mayor
Walter Gunderson has died.

9
00:00:18,956 --> 00:00:21,758
Well, you jinxed us, Garry.
Thanks a lot.

10
00:00:24,728 --> 00:00:32,602
Sync & corrections by honeybunny
www.addic7ed.com

11
00:00:41,612 --> 00:00:45,615
Walter Gunderson
served Pawnee for 39 years.

12
00:00:45,649 --> 00:00:47,583
And as per his final wish,

13
00:00:47,618 --> 00:00:49,652
his body will lie in state

14
00:00:49,686 --> 00:00:52,321
in the city council chambers
for a day,

15
00:00:52,323 --> 00:00:56,025
which is just a real cool thing
for a public space.

16
00:00:56,059 --> 00:00:58,327
Also, he sent us
a brief video message

17
00:00:58,362 --> 00:01:00,897
to be played for this event.

18
00:01:00,931 --> 00:01:03,466
Hello, Pawnee.

19
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:07,003
My time in office
has come to an end.

20
00:01:07,037 --> 00:01:09,105
A lot has been done.

21
00:01:09,139 --> 00:01:11,774
But I wasn't really
doing very much.

22
00:01:11,809 --> 00:01:14,210
I wasn't paying attention
most of the time.

23
00:01:14,244 --> 00:01:16,813
Fortunately,
the citizens of Pawnee

24
00:01:16,847 --> 00:01:18,748
didn't pay attention either.

25
00:01:18,782 --> 00:01:21,951
So if there's credit to take,

26
00:01:21,985 --> 00:01:23,719
I will humbly take it.

27
00:01:23,754 --> 00:01:27,690
And if there is blame...

28
00:01:27,724 --> 00:01:29,325
it's your fault.

29
00:01:29,359 --> 00:01:31,194
Thank you.

30
00:01:31,228 --> 00:01:33,062
Good-bye forever.

31
00:01:33,097 --> 00:01:34,363
Uh, okay.

32
00:01:34,398 --> 00:01:36,332
Well, that was really something.

33
00:01:36,366 --> 00:01:39,335
People are dying,
moving, retiring.

34
00:01:39,369 --> 00:01:41,671
Too many endings.
Not enough beginnings.

35
00:01:41,705 --> 00:01:45,108
We need something to begin,
and I have just the thing...

36
00:01:45,142 --> 00:01:48,211
an underground
dance competition.

37
00:01:48,245 --> 00:01:50,246
I'm realizing I know nothing
about the logistics

38
00:01:50,280 --> 00:01:52,114
of how to start an underground
dance competition,

39
00:01:52,149 --> 00:01:54,317
but someone here will.

40
00:01:54,351 --> 00:01:56,753
Hey, April, will you
help me out with something?

41
00:01:56,787 --> 00:01:57,787
No.

42
00:01:57,821 --> 00:01:59,188
Apparently as city manager,

43
00:01:59,223 --> 00:02:00,857
I'm in charge of appointing
an interim mayor

44
00:02:00,891 --> 00:02:02,525
until the special election.

45
00:02:02,559 --> 00:02:04,727
So why don't
you just appoint yourself?

46
00:02:04,762 --> 00:02:06,863
You're basically
running the town anyway.

47
00:02:06,897 --> 00:02:09,198
Well, I was a mayor once before.

48
00:02:09,233 --> 00:02:10,666
We all remember how that went.

49
00:02:10,701 --> 00:02:12,468
Oh, yeah, you completely
disgraced yourself

50
00:02:12,503 --> 00:02:14,637
and destroyed an entire town.

51
00:02:14,671 --> 00:02:16,439
Yeah, I said we all remember.

52
00:02:16,473 --> 00:02:18,274
Now, will you help me
find someone?

53
00:02:18,308 --> 00:02:20,109
It can be anyone
over the age of 30

54
00:02:20,144 --> 00:02:22,378
who's a good symbolic face
for the town.

55
00:02:22,413 --> 00:02:24,013
Fine, whatever.
I'll help you, okay?

56
00:02:24,048 --> 00:02:25,882
Thank you.
I told Garry he could help too.

57
00:02:25,916 --> 00:02:27,850
- What?
- Oh, notarizing a new mayor,

58
00:02:27,885 --> 00:02:30,520
that is... well, it's like
the ultimate notary adventure.

59
00:02:30,554 --> 00:02:32,321
Oh, it's big.

60
00:02:32,356 --> 00:02:34,123
Les-legally Blonde!

61
00:02:34,158 --> 00:02:35,792
Got you a little gift
in New York.

62
00:02:35,826 --> 00:02:37,293
You did?

63
00:02:37,327 --> 00:02:38,761
What did you get me?
Ooh-la-la.

64
00:02:38,796 --> 00:02:40,963
Men's Ferragamo loafers?

65
00:02:40,998 --> 00:02:42,498
What am I supposed
to do with these?

66
00:02:42,533 --> 00:02:44,100
Yeah, you're right.
I should probably keep them.

67
00:02:44,134 --> 00:02:46,536
They're a size 61/2.
Too small for you anyway.

68
00:02:46,570 --> 00:02:47,970
- How was your trip?
- Amazing.

69
00:02:48,005 --> 00:02:49,205
A lot of great meetings.

70
00:02:49,239 --> 00:02:51,040
Plus, Lucy and I
had the best time.

71
00:02:51,075 --> 00:02:52,375
It's for real, Leslie.

72
00:02:52,409 --> 00:02:54,010
We even went to a jewelry store
and looked at rings.

73
00:02:54,044 --> 00:02:55,411
No!

74
00:02:55,446 --> 00:02:57,780
Shia LaBeouf is one hell of
a jewelry designer, by the way.

75
00:02:57,815 --> 00:02:58,848
Man's really found his calling.

76
00:02:58,882 --> 00:03:00,183
This is perfect.

77
00:03:00,217 --> 00:03:01,484
With everything ending,

78
00:03:01,518 --> 00:03:03,753
you guys are the happy beginning
that we all need.

79
00:03:03,787 --> 00:03:05,788
You should propose to her,
right now, here.

80
00:03:05,823 --> 00:03:07,757
What better place to ask
a woman to marry you

81
00:03:07,791 --> 00:03:09,959
than an old man's
public memorial?

82
00:03:09,994 --> 00:03:11,160
Yeah, I think
I'm probably gonna wait.

83
00:03:11,195 --> 00:03:12,328
Plus, Lucy's not in town.

84
00:03:12,362 --> 00:03:13,529
She's in Philadelphia
visiting friends.

85
00:03:13,564 --> 00:03:14,931
She gets back tomorrow.

86
00:03:14,965 --> 00:03:16,566
Yeah, you'd probably want
her here for that, right?

87
00:03:16,600 --> 00:03:18,000
All right, I'm gonna find April.

88
00:03:18,035 --> 00:03:21,304
I got her a really nice
Burberry necktie.

89
00:03:21,338 --> 00:03:23,673
Gunderson was mayor
my entire life.

90
00:03:23,707 --> 00:03:27,110
Really makes you consider
the "postulence" of time.

91
00:03:27,144 --> 00:03:28,411
Sure.

92
00:03:28,445 --> 00:03:30,012
Death is natural, Andrew.

93
00:03:30,047 --> 00:03:32,782
We're born, we survive
as long as we're useful,

94
00:03:32,816 --> 00:03:34,283
and then we're killed,

95
00:03:34,318 --> 00:03:36,052
either by our body's
natural decay

96
00:03:36,086 --> 00:03:37,553
or by those
younger and stronger.

97
00:03:37,588 --> 00:03:38,955
Speak for yourself.

98
00:03:38,989 --> 00:03:41,023
Before I die, I'm freezing
my head like Ted Williams.

99
00:03:41,058 --> 00:03:42,859
Wait a thousand years,
thaw it out,

100
00:03:42,893 --> 00:03:45,395
slap it on a robot,
keep on balling.

101
00:03:45,429 --> 00:03:46,496
Ron.

102
00:03:46,530 --> 00:03:47,530
Carl.

103
00:03:47,564 --> 00:03:49,132
Donna, Andy, this is Carl.

104
00:03:49,166 --> 00:03:52,735
He owns the deli right next
to my barber Salvatore's shop.

105
00:03:52,770 --> 00:03:54,036
It's terrible, isn't it?

106
00:03:54,071 --> 00:03:57,240
First Salvatore
and now Mayor Gunderson.

107
00:03:57,274 --> 00:04:00,309
What? What happened?
Explain yourself!

108
00:04:00,344 --> 00:04:01,844
Oh, Ron, you didn't hear?

109
00:04:01,879 --> 00:04:03,846
Salvatore passed away yesterday.

110
00:04:03,881 --> 00:04:05,882
- No.
- Jeez.

111
00:04:05,916 --> 00:04:08,818
No, it can't be.

112
00:04:08,852 --> 00:04:11,988
Was he killed
by a younger, stronger barber?

113
00:04:12,022 --> 00:04:13,656
And now here to say a few words

114
00:04:13,690 --> 00:04:17,093
is Mayor Gunderson's
longtime friend and coworker

115
00:04:17,127 --> 00:04:18,428
Ethel Beavers.

116
00:04:18,462 --> 00:04:20,063
This is gonna be so sad.

117
00:04:20,097 --> 00:04:21,597
They worked together
for a long time.

118
00:04:21,632 --> 00:04:23,065
I'll be brief.

119
00:04:23,100 --> 00:04:25,168
Walter Gunderson and his wife

120
00:04:25,202 --> 00:04:26,769
had an open marriage.

121
00:04:26,804 --> 00:04:31,007
It kept him happy.
It kept his wife happy.

122
00:04:31,041 --> 00:04:32,542
Hi, Evelyn.

123
00:04:32,576 --> 00:04:35,178
And it definitely kept me happy.

124
00:04:35,212 --> 00:04:37,513
What is happening?

125
00:04:37,548 --> 00:04:40,650
Because for 46 wonderful years,

126
00:04:40,684 --> 00:04:42,585
he spent night after night

127
00:04:42,619 --> 00:04:47,056
exploring every nook and cranny
of my body.

128
00:04:48,592 --> 00:04:50,059
Grow up, you prudes.

129
00:04:50,093 --> 00:04:51,327
We're all adults.

130
00:04:51,361 --> 00:04:53,629
My only regret
is that I never told him

131
00:04:53,664 --> 00:04:55,364
how I really felt.

132
00:04:55,399 --> 00:04:57,066
So I'll say it now.

133
00:04:57,101 --> 00:04:59,435
I loved that man.

134
00:04:59,470 --> 00:05:02,572
And not just because
he was a dynamite lay.

135
00:05:07,444 --> 00:05:09,746
Good night, you animal.

136
00:05:09,780 --> 00:05:11,648
Tom, listen to Ethel.

137
00:05:11,682 --> 00:05:13,216
Ugh, no, it's too gross.

138
00:05:13,250 --> 00:05:14,717
No, listen to her message.

139
00:05:14,752 --> 00:05:16,586
You can't wait to tell someone
how you feel,

140
00:05:16,620 --> 00:05:19,255
because if you wait,
before you know it, boom,

141
00:05:19,290 --> 00:05:21,424
46 years later they're gone.

142
00:05:21,458 --> 00:05:22,425
You're right.

143
00:05:22,459 --> 00:05:23,726
We know we want
to be together forever.

144
00:05:23,761 --> 00:05:25,128
- So why wait?
- Exactly.

145
00:05:25,162 --> 00:05:26,462
And I will help you
with the proposal.

146
00:05:26,497 --> 00:05:27,463
What do you want to do?

147
00:05:27,498 --> 00:05:28,531
Off the top of my head,

148
00:05:28,565 --> 00:05:30,600
I guess my ideal proposal
might be

149
00:05:30,634 --> 00:05:32,435
a multiplatform
media experience,

150
00:05:32,469 --> 00:05:34,670
an action movie
with explosive graphics,

151
00:05:34,705 --> 00:05:36,906
fast cars, and a hero
with one mission...

152
00:05:36,940 --> 00:05:38,408
to propose to his lady.

153
00:05:38,442 --> 00:05:39,409
A hero named...

154
00:05:39,443 --> 00:05:41,244
Tom Haverford.

155
00:05:41,278 --> 00:05:43,813
- Okay!
- Yes!

156
00:05:43,847 --> 00:05:47,483
Oh, um, people grieve
in different ways.

157
00:05:49,615 --> 00:05:52,225
Listen, if you can't train
200 white doves

158
00:05:52,345 --> 00:05:53,912
in the next four hours
to spell out

159
00:05:53,947 --> 00:05:55,347
"Lucy, will you marry me?"

160
00:05:55,381 --> 00:05:57,549
then you have no business
calling yourself a pet store.

161
00:05:57,584 --> 00:05:59,318
Why can't everyone
share our commitment

162
00:05:59,352 --> 00:06:01,186
to the basic concept
of outrageous pageantry?

163
00:06:01,221 --> 00:06:02,921
I don't know, Tom.
I really don't.

164
00:06:02,956 --> 00:06:04,723
Oh, no,
what do you want, Leslie?

165
00:06:04,757 --> 00:06:07,259
Hey, Ian. I need
a gigantic banner that says,

166
00:06:07,293 --> 00:06:08,827
"Congratulations, Lucy and Tom,"

167
00:06:08,862 --> 00:06:09,828
and I need it by tomorrow.

168
00:06:09,863 --> 00:06:10,929
No way.
Impossible.

169
00:06:10,964 --> 00:06:12,297
Over the past 15 years,

170
00:06:12,332 --> 00:06:15,567
I have spent nearly $100,000
at your banner store.

171
00:06:15,602 --> 00:06:16,935
I have ordered banners

172
00:06:16,970 --> 00:06:18,337
for every personal
and professional event

173
00:06:18,371 --> 00:06:19,605
that I've ever organized.

174
00:06:19,639 --> 00:06:21,306
My credit card company
called me about it.

175
00:06:21,341 --> 00:06:22,774
Not to question the charges

176
00:06:22,809 --> 00:06:25,410
but to sincerely ask me
if I was mentally stable.

177
00:06:25,445 --> 00:06:27,546
See that Rolex Submariner
on your wrist, bro?

178
00:06:27,580 --> 00:06:28,814
That's 'cause of Leslie.

179
00:06:28,848 --> 00:06:30,315
You'll have the banner done.

180
00:06:31,584 --> 00:06:34,286
Hey, Bobby,
thanks for coming in.

181
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:36,455
Good to see you guys.
It's been a while.

182
00:06:36,489 --> 00:06:39,825
How's Leslie?
Is she still, um... uh...

183
00:06:39,859 --> 00:06:41,226
Oh.

184
00:06:41,261 --> 00:06:42,728
What was that thing
we ran for again?

185
00:06:42,762 --> 00:06:44,129
City councilor.

186
00:06:44,164 --> 00:06:45,898
I don't know.
All right, if you say so.

187
00:06:45,932 --> 00:06:48,634
I tell you, it's so hard to
remember boring stuff like that.

188
00:06:48,668 --> 00:06:50,702
Choosing to ignore
what you just said,

189
00:06:50,737 --> 00:06:53,272
we need an interim mayor
just for two months.

190
00:06:53,306 --> 00:06:55,974
And given your family name
and how well-liked you are,

191
00:06:56,009 --> 00:06:57,543
I thought you might
be interested.

192
00:06:57,577 --> 00:06:59,111
- Mayor?
- Yeah.

193
00:06:59,145 --> 00:07:00,746
Man, that'll be fun.

194
00:07:00,780 --> 00:07:02,414
God, I don't think
I can do it, though.

195
00:07:02,448 --> 00:07:04,550
Yeah, 'cause I'm getting ready
to go on a big trip,

196
00:07:04,584 --> 00:07:05,918
to space.

197
00:07:05,952 --> 00:07:07,319
That'll be really fun too.

198
00:07:07,353 --> 00:07:09,588
Everything in life is always
just so fun, right?

199
00:07:09,622 --> 00:07:10,789
It really is.

200
00:07:10,824 --> 00:07:13,192
See, this guy knows what's what.

201
00:07:13,226 --> 00:07:14,660
- Yeah.
- That was... yeah.

202
00:07:14,694 --> 00:07:16,194
Hey, Ben, have you ever
been to space?

203
00:07:16,229 --> 00:07:18,263
You should check it out.
Seriously.

204
00:07:18,298 --> 00:07:19,665
I'm sure the Russian guys
who built the rocket

205
00:07:19,699 --> 00:07:21,200
- would be cool with it.
- Really?

206
00:07:21,234 --> 00:07:23,235
Just one thing,
do you have $600,000?

207
00:07:23,269 --> 00:07:25,337
It's just, that's what
they need for a deposit.

208
00:07:25,371 --> 00:07:27,739
Oh.
Well, no.

209
00:07:27,774 --> 00:07:29,107
I've already been to space.

210
00:07:29,142 --> 00:07:31,443
I was the second person
to walk on the moon.

211
00:07:31,477 --> 00:07:33,579
Buzz Aldrin.
Nice to meet you.

212
00:07:33,613 --> 00:07:34,847
Nice try.

213
00:07:34,881 --> 00:07:38,383
That's the guy from Toy Story.

214
00:07:39,552 --> 00:07:41,186
We're so sorry, Ron.

215
00:07:41,221 --> 00:07:42,588
You guys were close?

216
00:07:42,622 --> 00:07:45,157
I've seen Salvatore
the first Tuesday of the month

217
00:07:45,191 --> 00:07:47,693
for the past four decades.

218
00:07:47,727 --> 00:07:49,995
Same exact thing every time.

219
00:07:50,029 --> 00:07:52,097
I paid him $8.

220
00:07:52,131 --> 00:07:53,665
I sat in the same chair.

221
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:55,968
Salvatore put
the same cape over me.

222
00:07:56,002 --> 00:07:58,837
Then he'd always ask me
about the same thing...

223
00:07:58,872 --> 00:08:02,441
nothing.

224
00:08:02,475 --> 00:08:04,142
It was perfect.

225
00:08:04,177 --> 00:08:07,246
Can't delay this forever.
Excuse me.

226
00:08:10,116 --> 00:08:12,985
The three most important people
in a man's life

227
00:08:13,019 --> 00:08:17,890
are his barber, his butcher,
and his lover.

228
00:08:19,492 --> 00:08:21,593
I have lost one of those.

229
00:08:22,729 --> 00:08:25,030
Here's a tenner, Sal.

230
00:08:28,535 --> 00:08:30,002
As you know,
I don't believe in tipping,

231
00:08:30,036 --> 00:08:32,237
so I will collect
my change from your wife.

232
00:08:35,408 --> 00:08:39,378
I had an appointment with
Salvatore scheduled for Tuesday.

233
00:08:39,412 --> 00:08:41,313
Look how raggedy my hair is.

234
00:08:41,347 --> 00:08:43,549
What am I supposed to be,
some kind or rock star?

235
00:08:45,385 --> 00:08:47,419
Okay, Tom, there's your mark.

236
00:08:47,453 --> 00:08:48,887
You'll enter from the front.

237
00:08:48,922 --> 00:08:50,122
Ted, are we rolling?

238
00:08:50,156 --> 00:08:52,257
I think so.
I don't really know.

239
00:08:52,292 --> 00:08:54,026
Just please be careful
with my store.

240
00:08:54,060 --> 00:08:56,228
Okay, quiet on the set!

241
00:08:56,262 --> 00:08:58,664
Action.

242
00:09:00,266 --> 00:09:01,533
Hello.

243
00:09:01,568 --> 00:09:04,269
Would you like to see
some rings, Agent Haverford?

244
00:09:04,304 --> 00:09:05,671
Why are you doing an accent?

245
00:09:05,705 --> 00:09:07,139
I came up with
a backstory for my character.

246
00:09:07,173 --> 00:09:08,607
She's married
to a French billionaire,

247
00:09:08,641 --> 00:09:11,410
and she has a twin sister,
identical, and they keep...

248
00:09:11,444 --> 00:09:12,511
Leslie, you have one line.

249
00:09:12,545 --> 00:09:15,214
Well, I committed to the role.

250
00:09:15,248 --> 00:09:16,515
Hello.

251
00:09:16,549 --> 00:09:19,184
Would you like to see
some gorgeous jewelry?

252
00:09:19,219 --> 00:09:22,688
We have the most rare diamonds
in the world.

253
00:09:22,722 --> 00:09:25,858
I'll take that one.
The most expensive one.

254
00:09:25,892 --> 00:09:28,494
Not so fast,
Haver-fraud.

255
00:09:30,096 --> 00:09:31,363
Ah, zut alors!

256
00:09:31,397 --> 00:09:34,266
Get 'em, boys!

257
00:09:34,300 --> 00:09:36,668
Freeze!
Stunt double.

258
00:09:36,703 --> 00:09:38,036
Tom.

259
00:09:38,071 --> 00:09:39,204
